AB  - Macadamia (Proteaceae) is a rainforest genus indigenous to Queensland and northern New South Wales, Australia. It includes four species, two of which, and their hybrids, are grown commercially for their high-value nuts in Australia and other countries. Macadamia is now being grown in several orchards and in gardens on the Bolaven plateau in southern Lao People's Democratic Republic (PDR). In November 2018, leaf spot disease symptoms were observed on young leaves of macadamia trees in a demonstration garden 15 km west of Paksong, on the Bolaven Plateau in Champasak Province, Lao PDR. A fungus isolated from the leaf spots was identified by morphological and DNA sequence comparisons as Calonectria pseudoreteaudii. This is the first report of this species in the Lao PDR. This report is one of a continuing series of first reports of crop pathogens in the southern region of the Lao PDR. These are outcomes of a continuing cooperative program in diagnostics, integrated disease management (IDM) and biosecurity, involving staff of the Champasak Provincial Agriculture and Forestry Office (PAFO) and plant pathologists in Australia, New Zealand, and Italy. The program has been supported by the Crawford Fund of Australia since 2009 in cooperation with state and federal government agencies. Short-term and long-term volunteer plant pathologists are sponsored primarily by the Australian Government Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) through the Australian Volunteers Program, and the Crawford Fund. The diagnostic studies undertaken during the program are designed to support the professional development of Laos provincial and district staff and provide a basis for developing IDM strategies for extension to small-holder farmers. Central to these studies are regular surveys of established and novel vegetable, field, and fruit crops, and collection of diseased specimens. It is important to monitor novel crops early in their evaluation in the local agro-ecosystems; failure to recognise the potential impact of disease on novel crops can lead to serious financial losses for small-holder farmers, who are usually resource poor. All culturable pathogens are deposited in the International Collection of Microorganisms from Plants (ICMP) in New Zealand. Dried herbarium specimens are deposited in the Plant Pathology and Mycology Herbarium (DAR) of the New South Wales Department of Primary Industries (NSW DPI) in Australia. The formal publication of first reports creates a knowledge legacy as well as valuable teaching aids in training programs. Australia and other countries also benefit from such cooperative diagnostic studies; they provide early warning of emerging pathogens as well as providing specimens for use in refining existing detection protocols for exotic pathogens.
