AB  - The Global Value Chain approach and related 'chain approaches' within economic geography have proved to be important frameworks for conducting empirical studies of agricultural economies and their implications for smallholders and rural communities. Such studies have their strengths in explaining how global dynamics impact on local communities, but they are relatively weak in explaining commercial configurations at the local level. This paper examines the differences in the structure of trade networks between actors in the small-scale oil-palm industry in four neighbouring settlements in rural Ghana. The exploratory application of social network analysis (SNA) is used to uncover the complexity of the networks in the trade in products and services in the local small-scale palm-oil sector, which exist parallel to a more formal large-scale sector. As a result, distinct local patterns of economic organisation are identified, indicating that SNA is a valuable tool for uncovering the territorial complexities of economic networks that other research methodologies may fail to capture. Hence, SNA is also an important and novel methodology for policy-making aimed at supporting and regulating an increasingly commercial agricultural economy in rural Africa.
